7 Like the Sicilian bull who bellowed first 8 with the weeping of the one, and this was right, 9 that had tempered it with his file,
10 he bellowed with the voice of the afflicted, 11 so that, even though it was of bronze, 12 still it seemed pierced by the pain;
13 thus, for not having a way or opening 14 from the beginning in the fire, in its language 15 were converted the harsh words.

55 Now who are you, I pray you tell me;
56 do not be harder than others have been,
57 if your name holds its head in the world.

58 After that the fire had somewhat blazed 59 in its manner, the sharp point moved 60 here, there, and then gave such a breath:
61 «If I believed that my answer was to 62 a person who ever returned to the world, 63 this flame would stay without more shaking;
64 but since already no one from this bottom 65 ever returned alive, if I hear the truth, 66 without fear of infamy I answer you.»

67 I was a man of arms, and then a rope-maker,
68 believing, thus girded, to make amends;
69 and certainly my belief came whole,

70 if it were not the great priest, to whom evil take him!,
71 who returned me to the first sins;
72 and how and where, I want him to understand.

100 And then he said again: “Your heart does not suspect;
101 until now I absolve you, and you teach me to do
102 as Penestrinus casts [things] on the earth.”

